We need to “extract” the “main business revenue” from the many transactions. In our books only the “Sale”‐type transactions form the primary “main business revenue” (that is, revenue generated by operating “product sales”). In our data the “Sale” rows include a net–or “after_tax_amount” column (which is our “net sales”). Thus, to get the “final main business revenue item” we sum together the “after_tax_amount” from every transaction whose type is “Sale.”

Below is how you can “simulate” the process step–by–step. (Note: In the table the columns are listed in order. For a given “Sale” row, the columns are: id, type, date, recorded_date, amount, recorded_amount, …, customer_id, tax_amount, after_tax_amount, cost_amount, profit, …)

We go over each row marked “Sale” (only those rows are part of the operating revenue):

1. For example, the first sale row is
  Sale20240103003: after_tax_amount = 158418.90  
2. Next, Sale20240104004: after_tax_amount = 331831.77

By summing all these “after_tax_amount” values – we obtain:

  158418.90 + 331831.77 + 42037.71 + 221319.22 + 531266.17 + 215804.96 + 276652.35 + 127976.95 + 533664.92 + 11395.11 + 214420.81 + 22746.27 + 22335.05 + 216628.01 + 109466.12 + 10879.77 + 288937.56 + 12262.83 + 239379.37 + 22160.58 + 119631.37 + 223300.96 + 45478.97 + 22444.23 + 39546.54 + 119610.68 + 95162.64 + 255256.79 + 22000.25 + 12258.70 + 263890.20 + 232984.99 + 24297.58 + 251272.87 + 49232.46 + 116153.44 + 23859.62 + 121920.26 = 5647886.98

Thus the main business revenue (the sum of all sale revenues “after tax”) is 5,647,886.98.
